To run code when the user refreshes the browser in a React application, you can use the `useEffect` hook with an empty dependency array, which ensures that the effect runs only once when the component mounts. Additionally, you can attach an event listener to the `beforeunload` event on the `window` object to handle logic right before the user leaves or refreshes the page. Here is a basic example:

```javascript
import React, { useEffect } from 'react';

function MyComponent() {
  useEffect(() => {
    const handleRefresh = (event) => {
      // Add code you want to run on refresh here
      console.log('Page is refreshing');
    };

    window.addEventListener('beforeunload', handleRefresh);

    // Cleanup the event listener on component unmount
    return () => {
      window.removeEventListener('beforeunload', handleRefresh);
    };
  }, []);

  return <div>Your Component Content</div>;
}

export default MyComponent;
```

This setup ensures that your desired code runs when a user refreshes the browser. Be cautious with the `beforeunload` event as it may not trigger certain asynchronous operations to complete in time before the refresh occurs.

